  "format": "The year-end lists. Sean Fennessey, Amanda Dobbins, and Chris Ryan bring in Adam Nayman for four ranked top fives, revealed five to one, then a long run of honorable mentions. First the news: the Warner Bros. sale, Leonardo DiCaprio all but confirming Heat 2 with Michael Mann, and where awards season stands with One Battle After Another out front.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The news",
      "note": "the Warner Bros. sale, Heat 2, awards season",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Zootopia 2",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "$570 million opening weekend, $220 million-plus of it in China. Overt Shining and Silence of the Lambs references, and a decade of Judy-and-Nick shipping the film seems to know about."
        },
        {
          "title": "Zootopia",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "The original, which Sean argues did something new for a wide-release animated film: animals running a whole society, jobs and all. The sloth at the DMV."
        },
        {
          "title": "Rango",
          "year": 2011,
          "note": "Chris's tangent: a frog-sheriff retelling of Chinatown, stuffed with movie references."
        },
        {
          "title": "Heat",
          "year": 1995,
          "note": "DiCaprio confirms to Deadline that he's doing Heat 2 with Michael Mann. The group games out whether he's the De Niro part and who could play against him."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Was 2025 a good year at the movies?",
      "note": "Adam joins; high ceiling, low floor",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "A Minecraft Movie",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "The year's one 'rocket ship,' and the ticket Sean bought on April 18th that turned a bleak year around. Everyone agrees the top of the year is bright and the middle is hazy."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Adam Nayman's top five",
      "ranked": true,
      "subject": "Adam Nayman",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "It Was Just an Accident",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Jafar Panahi's Palme d'Or winner, shot unofficially in Iran. A mistaken-identity revenge thriller that's slapstick and brutal at once, with the best last two scenes of the year."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Shrouds",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Cronenberg's grief film about a widower who builds a way to watch his wife's body decay. Adam's watched it three or four times and loves how close it comes to seeming like a terrible movie."
        },
        {
          "title": "One Battle After Another",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Has it third and admits he's already tired of the discourse. More interested in the negative reactions, and in finding the weird, ambiguous PTA inside a huge movie."
        },
        {
          "title": "Cloud",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Kiyoshi Kurosawa. An online reseller angers his customers into hunting him down; a moody thriller that turns into a full warehouse shootout. Sean's shorthand: Heat for fuck-ups."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Secret Agent",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Kleber Mendonça Filho's Brazilian thriller under the late-'70s dictatorship. Wagner Moura as a functionary forging passports while hitmen close in, all of it a love letter to movie-palace culture and shadowed by Jaws."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Amanda Dobbins's top five",
      "note": "the theme: everyone going for it",
      "ranked": true,
      "subject": "Amanda Dobbins",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "One Battle After Another",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "An instant five-star masterpiece for her. Parenthood, scale, and all of film history rooted in the current moment."
        },
        {
          "title": "Marty Supreme",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Josh Safdie's ping-pong movie, and the clearest case of her theme: a cast and crew going as big as they can."
        },
        {
          "title": "Die My Love",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Lynne Ramsay, with Jennifer Lawrence and Robert Pattinson. Postpartum psychosis played feral and physical, and the most she laughed in a theater. She started 2025 three months postpartum, then left home in the LA fires."
        },
        {
          "title": "If I Had Legs I'd Kick You",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Mary Bronstein; Rose Byrne alone with a sick kid. The most nauseous she's been in a theater all year, meant as a compliment, and a systemic critique of how everything fails a mother."
        },
        {
          "title": "Train Dreams",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Familiar indie moves, the voiceover and the flashbacks and the trees, that add up to far more than their parts. Grief and guilt shown, not told, right to the last line."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Chris Ryan's top five",
      "ranked": true,
      "subject": "Chris Ryan",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "28 Years Later",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Danny Boyle and Alex Garland, with Alfie Williams and a Ralph Fiennes performance he'll never forget. He saw it as his mother was dying, and it never left him."
        },
        {
          "title": "One Battle After Another",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Number two by the thinnest personal margin. The cinematic experience of the year, and an adaptation of Vineland he can't stop taking apart."
        },
        {
          "title": "Weapons",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Three viewings in. What he thinks it's about: why we need horror at all, and the monsters we invent to explain the tragedies that befall a community. The kids running with their arms out."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sinners",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "On a second viewing he finds it almost underrated. The musicality, the ecstatic sweat of it, the most physically engaged he felt in a theater outside F1."
        },
        {
          "title": "Eephus",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Carson Lund's monument to hanging out: two rec-league teams playing the last game on a field about to be paved into a school. Made him feel 17 watching a Jarmusch movie."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Sean Fennessey's top five",
      "note": "thwarted male ambition and parenthood",
      "ranked": true,
      "subject": "Sean Fennessey",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "One Battle After Another",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Obviously his number one. Thwarted ambition, parenthood, and a film he finds almost fake for how connected to it he feels."
        },
        {
          "title": "Eddington",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Ari Aster's best, he argues: docudrama and satire at once. People dislike it because it makes them feel bad about specific things that happened, and about that final shot."
        },
        {
          "title": "No Other Choice",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Park Chan-wook's Westlake adaptation. A laid-off paper-company man schemes to eliminate his rivals for the few jobs left. Elaborate and absurd, with a showy formal streak."
        },
        {
          "title": "Marty Supreme",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Safdie's film on how a lot of men are in their 20s: fast-talking and gifted, in a way that wears you out. Seen once, months ago, and the cherry on top of the movie year for him."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sinners",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Popped in the 4K and got pulled back by the score. His prime example of Hollywood filmmaking: someone through the system making something at scale that stays deeply personal."
        }
      ]
    },
